WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:03.960
Foreign

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:14.520
[Music] I'm Norman Wildberger. We're setting&nbsp;
out a new foundation for arithmetic and algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:21.420
in fact, mathematics more generally, based&nbsp;
on multi-sets and thinking about numbers and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:29.220
polynomials and consequent algebra, all built in&nbsp;
terms of these multi-sets. A key sort of novelty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:33.720
in this approach is that we end up having to&nbsp;
adopt some of the 20th-century physicists'&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:41.100
ideas having to do with particle-antiparticle&nbsp;
duality to create a theory of negative numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:46.200
So we've done that, and now we're in a position&nbsp;
to reap some of the very important consequences.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:55.680
I'm aspiring here not just to create a new&nbsp;
foundation for the subject but also to position us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.460 --> 00:01:01.140
in a way that we can see things in a&nbsp;
new light. You're going to see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.140 --> 00:01:07.320
happening very strongly today. We're going to&nbsp;
be looking at polynomials with a new point of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:12.360
view that will open up all kinds of interesting&nbsp;
developments, and in fact, it will turn out that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:17.940
we will end up being able to reinterpret&nbsp;
some very important 20th-century physics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:23.520
developments in terms of this very elementary&nbsp;
algebra. So we're heading in that direction.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:29.280
Okay, so we're going to be talking about integral&nbsp;
polynomials. Let me remind you that a poly number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:33.420
itself is an mset of natural numbers. For&nbsp;
example, here there's an mset of natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:40.680
numbers interpreted as 2 plus alpha plus 3 alpha&nbsp;
to the 4, and here's our usual convention in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:48.480
the algebraic calculus course, for example, for&nbsp;
expressing such a poly number. Now somewhat novel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:55.860
an integral poly number is an mset of integers&nbsp;
now, so that includes not just natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.860 --> 00:02:03.480
like this but also negative numbers. I like to&nbsp;
often express negative numbers with the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:07.800
numbers with a bar over them, so this is minus&nbsp;
three, that's minus three, that's minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:14.400
etc. Now this corresponds on the polynomial side,&nbsp;
in terms of powers of alpha, to the following:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:21.540
this is really two, there's two of these alpha&nbsp;
to the minus three or three bar, there is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:26.520
single alpha to the one bar or alpha to the minus&nbsp;
one, there's a one, and then there's three alpha.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:32.940
Perhaps more usually, if we sort of adopt the&nbsp;
usual convention for negative signs, in a more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:39.840
familiar way it would be 2 alpha to the minus 3&nbsp;
plus alpha to the minus 1 plus 1 plus 3 alpha. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:46.020
in algebra, this is not a polynomial because there&nbsp;
are negative powers of the variable appearing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:55.080
sometimes called a Laurent polynomial or&nbsp;
sometimes a rational function. In any case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.080 --> 00:03:01.980
we are going to augment this notation, make it a&nbsp;
little bit bigger, to allow us to incorporate also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:05.820
coefficients of negative powers of&nbsp;
alpha in sort of an obvious way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:11.580
but we're going to have a little bit of an&nbsp;
addition now. So the one plus three alpha will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:19.260
be represented by the one here and the three, so&nbsp;
this would be the usual poly number story. What&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:24.780
I'm now going to do is include the coefficients&nbsp;
of alpha to the minus one, alpha to the minus 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:30.960
alpha to the minus 3 up above here, and now&nbsp;
there's a sort of a symmetry here which will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:37.020
become very important in this lecture. There's&nbsp;
a symmetry here where this central object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.820
which is the coefficient of just the constant&nbsp;
term, sort of plays a central role now. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:46.560
strictly positive and strictly negative ones are&nbsp;
on either side of it, and so to make that clear,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:55.800
I'm going to put a double bar there. So those two&nbsp;
bars are going to frame the constant term or the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.800 --> 00:04:02.580
alpha to the zero coefficient. All right,&nbsp;
so that's what an integral poly number is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:07.020
and we're going to be seeing some&nbsp;
interesting things about these things today.

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:14.040
Now, we particularly like doing arithmetic in the&nbsp;
domain of integers, so we're also going to allow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:22.620
ourselves to consider integers as coefficients of&nbsp;
our powers of alpha, and that manifests itself in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:29.880
having anti-integers inside our mset defining the&nbsp;
poly number or the integral poly number. So have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:41.280
a look at this thing here: this is an ordinary&nbsp;
poly number with natural number entries here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:45.960
but some of them have antis. So there's a&nbsp;
zero anti-zero anti-one, one, one, three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:53.160
anti, and these two zero antis are representing&nbsp;
the number minus two. So if we just had an mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:59.610
zero anti-zero anti or anti-zero anti-zero, that&nbsp;
would be the number minus two or two bar. There&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:59.610 --> 00:05:05.280
are still three alphas here, represented by these&nbsp;
three ones, and there's a single alpha cubed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:13.620
but there's an anti here, so we have to take&nbsp;
minus that. So in conventional notation with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:18.720
the more usual conventions, this would be&nbsp;
minus two plus three alpha minus alpha cubed.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:29.700
So that's a poly number, but now we can combine&nbsp;
these two different roles of integers here and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:40.620
consider integral poly numbers also with integer&nbsp;
coefficients. So that means that inside here we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:46.320
have integers, not just natural numbers but also&nbsp;
negative numbers like negative one and negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:52.980
two, etc., but we also have antis. So this is&nbsp;
a two bar, anti-one bar, anti-one bar, anti.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:58.920
It corresponds to this two bar, corresponds to&nbsp;
alpha to the minus two or alpha, it's the two bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:05.880
but the anti means that there's minus one of&nbsp;
them. So there's a minus one or minus alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:10.500
to the minus two represented by that thing&nbsp;
there. There's two of these one bar antis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:16.020
so the one bar is telling us that we're&nbsp;
talking about alpha to the minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:21.720
and the antis representing the fact that we&nbsp;
don't have two of them, we have minus two of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:29.940
them. So minus two alpha to the minus one or,&nbsp;
in more legally, plus two bar alpha one bar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:37.020
and then there's a zero that represents one, and&nbsp;
these three twos give us three alpha squared.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:45.780
So if we want the usual notation for negative&nbsp;
numbers, we could also rewrite the mset. Instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:50.400
of having two bar, we could write minus two, so&nbsp;
instead of the one bar we could write minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:57.180
etc. So it amounts to the same thing, but&nbsp;
there's a lot of negatives here, and there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.180 --> 00:07:03.180
is definitely the possibility of confusion here&nbsp;
with this minus sign. The minus sign being here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:08.460
even though it's very familiar, it's in the place&nbsp;
where an operation usually is. So there's an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:12.540
operation sign there, and it looks like there's&nbsp;
an operation sign here, but you have to sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:17.460
interpret that the operation sign is not really&nbsp;
an operation sign; it's rather negating the two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:25.500
So this is not really optimal notation, so gently&nbsp;
I want to move you a little bit towards something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:35.640
more in this direction where the operations&nbsp;
and the negations are more clearly delineated.

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:41.820
Now when we're doing calculus or analysis,&nbsp;
there is a big difference between the world of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:47.100
polynomials and the world of rational functions,&nbsp;
what we're calling the difference between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:53.280
polynomials and integral polynumbers. So that's&nbsp;
what you get when you view all these things as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.280 --> 00:08:01.440
functions. In 20th-century mathematics, the idea&nbsp;
of a function was all-pervasive. A lot of things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:08.640
were attempted to be framed in terms of functions,&nbsp;
a rule that assigns something of a certain kind as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:16.080
input and then gives you an output of some other&nbsp;
potentially different kind. So in my view, this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:25.980
sort of active role of functions is overplayed.&nbsp;
It's too frequent a concept in modern mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.980 --> 00:08:34.080
and it leads to a lot of confusion because this&nbsp;
dynamic aspect of taking an input and doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:41.460
something to get an output necessarily really&nbsp;
involves a deep dive into computational issues,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:48.840
issues of programming, issues of computation,&nbsp;
issues then correspondingly of memory and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:57.780
language, etc. So I'm going to strongly advocate&nbsp;
to you that you should not think about polynomials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:03.600
or poly numbers or integral polynomials as&nbsp;
functions primarily. If you're an undergraduate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:08.580
and have done a mathematics degree, this will&nbsp;
be sort of so ingrained into your thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.580 --> 00:09:13.080
that it will be a bit of a challenge to move&nbsp;
back from that, but it has a lot of benefits.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:18.540
Okay, so the usual story, let's look at it with&nbsp;
a distinction between these two examples. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:26.670
here is a poly number on this side, and here's an&nbsp;
integral poly number. This one is 0, 1, anti-3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:32.820
3, corresponding to the polynomial 1 minus alpha&nbsp;
plus two alpha cubed in the usual notation. Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:37.980
there's a kind of a negation of this in some&nbsp;
sense, so we're sort of replacing each of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.980 --> 00:09:45.000
numbers here with their negatives. So we have a&nbsp;
three bar, three bar, a one bar, anti, and a zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:51.780
and that corresponds to the integral poly number&nbsp;
2 times alpha to the minus 3 minus alpha to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.780 --> 00:10:00.600
minus 1 plus 1. Now in a calculus course or an&nbsp;
analysis course, you would look at these things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:06.120
in terms of functions. You'd say, aha, this thing&nbsp;
here really represents a function, say y equals P&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:13.740
of x given by this polynomial. So you input x and&nbsp;
you output y, and correspondingly this thing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:21.720
is also a function, 2 over x cubed minus 1 over&nbsp;
x plus one. You input x, you output y. But in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:30.120
the world of functions, these things are hugely&nbsp;
different for one obvious reason: as a function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:39.960
this thing here with the x in the denominator&nbsp;
requires you to avoid an input of zero. Because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:46.020
if you put in zero here, it doesn't give you&nbsp;
anything that's defined. So the domain of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:51.360
thing is automatically different from the domain&nbsp;
of this, but also visually, in terms of a graph,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:57.660
they are very different kinds of objects. There's&nbsp;
a graph of this thing here, a sort of familiar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:07.260
cubic kind of shape, and here is perhaps less&nbsp;
familiar, somewhat hyperbolic shape with this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:12.060
singularity at x equals zero represented by&nbsp;
these two branches that go up and down here.

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:17.940
So a manifestation of the huge difference&nbsp;
between these two things is when we come to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:26.160
fundamental question of integration in calculus.&nbsp;
Now if you say integrate this thing from, say, one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:32.940
to two over this interval here, the area of that&nbsp;
turns out to be exactly seven. That's an exact&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:40.860
calculation. Well, over here the corresponding&nbsp;
integral from one to two of this function turns&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:46.380
out, if I ask my computer, it's 7 over 4 minus&nbsp;
log 2. It's a standard integral that high school&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:53.040
students or undergraduates learn to do. Now we say&nbsp;
this answer here rather glibly, but really this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:53.040 --> 00:12:01.500
answer is a hugely computationally problematic&nbsp;
because this log 2 here represents a process which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:06.660
doesn't actually terminate, so you can't actually&nbsp;
compute it. So the question about whether there is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:12.300
an "it" that we're legitimately talking about here&nbsp;
is highly questionable. If you ask your computer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:17.760
well, it'll just spew out some number of digits,&nbsp;
but it's clear that you're not able to really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:23.820
obtain this thing exactly. So it's important&nbsp;
to state, as I've done in many places, this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.820 --> 00:12:32.340
thing over here is intrinsically an approximate&nbsp;
calculation, while this one over here is exact.

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:38.520
So there is a world of difference between&nbsp;
these two computations. This is really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:44.760
applied mathematics, and over here this is pure&nbsp;
mathematics. Moreover, in the algebraic calculus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:50.940
course, we learn that we can do this kind of&nbsp;
integral without any of the infinite machinery&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.940 --> 00:12:57.420
that's used in classical calculus or analysis&nbsp;
courses, in terms of Riemann integration, in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.420 --> 00:13:04.080
of setting up Riemann sums and subdividing things&nbsp;
and having rectangles and upper and lower bounds,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:11.880
etc., and then taking some limit as the net or&nbsp;
the size of the rectangles goes to zero. We can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:19.620
completely avoid that and stay completely&nbsp;
in a purely polynomial, purely finite sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:26.400
of calculating algebraic situation. So that's&nbsp;
a big departure from the usual calculus story&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:34.080
found in the algebraic calculus course lectures&nbsp;
over on the Wild Egg Mathematics channel. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:40.680
this really is an exact theory. We do not need&nbsp;
Riemann integration or Lebesgue integration,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:46.920
absolutely not. We can address this kind&nbsp;
of integral in a completely algebraic way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:49.260
but this thing here is necessarily approximate.

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:53.400
You can see that from the calculus&nbsp;
point of view, there is in fact, yes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:53.400 --> 00:14:00.480
a huge difference between this object and this&nbsp;
object, especially when we view them as functions.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:06.060
But I'm going to ask you here, because&nbsp;
we're doing arithmetic, we're doing algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.060 --> 00:14:13.140
to step back from this calculus orientation,&nbsp;
calculus over there, and look in this direction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:20.580
rather at algebra. When we're just looking at&nbsp;
the algebraic side, the distinction between these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:28.320
two things is much less obvious. In fact, they're&nbsp;
actually very close to being sort of symmetrical.

00:14:29.040 --> 00:14:34.380
So we're taking an algebraic approach; we're&nbsp;
letting go of the function concept. How then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:41.340
are we to interpret what the meaning of these&nbsp;
poly numbers are, whether they're poly numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:48.240
or integral poly numbers? Let me give you an&nbsp;
alternate way of thinking about what these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:54.000
things are or at least how to interpret them&nbsp;
in a kind of a visual or a physical fashion.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:55.320 --> 00:14:59.760
Actually, the question of what they are&nbsp;
is already contained in the definition:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:04.680
they are just multi-sets of natural numbers&nbsp;
or multi-sets of integers. That's what they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:11.520
actually are. But now the question is, how do we&nbsp;
think about them? So here is what I'm proposing:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:19.200
that we're going to think about these things as&nbsp;
densities or measures. It's like we have a number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:23.460
line, and it's actually sort of a discrete&nbsp;
number line for us currently. So, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.460 --> 00:15:28.800
imagine the natural numbers sort of strung out&nbsp;
on a line here: there's zero, there's one, we'd&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:33.060
mark these things, there's two, three, etc. We're&nbsp;
going to think about a poly number like this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.060 --> 00:15:40.440
2 minus alpha plus 3 alpha to the fourth, as being&nbsp;
a bunch of weights which are positioned over these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:46.140
various natural number positions. The weights can&nbsp;
be bigger or they can be smaller, they can also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.140 --> 00:15:50.520
be negative, corresponding to sort of like, you&nbsp;
know, an upward force instead of a downward force.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:59.340
It's like a density or a measure. So this thing&nbsp;
here, 2 minus alpha plus 3 alpha to the fourth,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:06.360
it's going to be represented physically or&nbsp;
visually by this mass distribution. So the way you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:10.620
should think about this, here's the number line,&nbsp;
and you see here there's a kind of a stack of two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:16.620
things. So think of this as like a unit weight of&nbsp;
some kind, a little metal bar perhaps. So there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:22.140
two of them stacked up on top of zero, that's&nbsp;
corresponding to that two. Down here there's sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:27.480
of one in the negative direction, corresponding to&nbsp;
a negative force, so it's down in that direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:27.480 --> 00:16:32.160
that's corresponding to the minus alpha. Over&nbsp;
here there's three of them over the four, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:32.160 --> 00:16:39.660
corresponding to three alpha to the four. Having&nbsp;
done that, the transition to an integral poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:48.360
number or an I-poly is not hard. We're just going&nbsp;
to extend this story where now the base number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:48.360 --> 00:16:54.060
line goes into two directions. Now zero is in&nbsp;
the middle there somewhere, and one is over here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:54.060 --> 00:16:58.620
and two is there, and over on this side minus one,&nbsp;
minus two, etc. So it extends in this direction as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.620 --> 00:17:05.880
well as this direction. So now we have more room&nbsp;
to put weights, positive or negative. That's all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:13.200
we're doing, we're just extending the number line&nbsp;
from sort of a one-sided discrete framework to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:19.740
two-sided discrete framework. So this thing&nbsp;
here, alpha to the minus three, minus three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:24.660
alpha to the minus two, plus four, plus alpha&nbsp;
squared, there it's represented. So there's an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:29.520
alpha to the minus three represented by this point&nbsp;
here, minus three on our number line, and there is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:34.800
a weight of one because there's one of these.&nbsp;
Then over minus two or under minus two there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.800 --> 00:17:41.940
a weight of three because it's minus three alpha&nbsp;
to the minus two. Over zero there's four, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:41.940 --> 00:17:49.140
representing that thing, and over the two there's&nbsp;
just a single one representing the alpha squared.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:55.980
So this is visualized as a density or measure on&nbsp;
the positive number line, essentially a discrete&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:55.980 --> 00:18:00.120
number line indexed by natural numbers, while&nbsp;
this one over here is visualized as a density&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.120 --> 00:18:06.840
or measure on the entire two-sided number line,&nbsp;
which is again discrete and labeled by integers.

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:13.800
So in this sort of continuum here, or this sort&nbsp;
of step-by-step, there are also more elaborate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:13.800 --> 00:18:19.200
algebraic objects, also built from poly numbers&nbsp;
in a natural way, called rational functions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:26.940
which are just quotients of poly numbers. That&nbsp;
is a bigger theory in some sense. You can,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:30.240
of course, think about these things as&nbsp;
being sort of special cases of this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:36.660
but we should just be aware that further on&nbsp;
down the road we do ultimately want to talk&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:41.520
about these things as well. From the calculus&nbsp;
point of view, these things are even much more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:47.460
complicated and sophisticated than the problems&nbsp;
that we get with the I-poly and the 1 over x.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:54.060
The complexity is massively bigger. That's not&nbsp;
properly understood in most calculus courses.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.660 --> 00:19:01.440
But we're sticking here with this framework. Now&nbsp;
we have a somewhat balanced point of view on how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.440 --> 00:19:05.400
to think about what poly numbers are, how to&nbsp;
think about what integral poly numbers are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:10.200
and they're pretty well the same kinds&nbsp;
of things, just over different domains.

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:15.120
Let me explain how you should think about the&nbsp;
arithmetic of these integral poly numbers with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:20.520
this sort of density or measure point of view.&nbsp;
The addition is pretty easy. Here's an example:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:24.780
p is alpha to the minus two plus one plus two&nbsp;
alpha, alpha to the minus two, that weight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.780 --> 00:19:30.600
the one over the zero, and the two stacked on&nbsp;
top of the one representing two alpha. Over here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:37.560
is another one, minus two alpha to the minus&nbsp;
one, so weight of minus two at minus one and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:47.880
a weight of one at one. If we add these things,&nbsp;
what we do is we just add the two densities,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.880 --> 00:19:53.520
we just combine them in the obvious way. So if we&nbsp;
combine these two things, there's the number line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:58.140
so that density is coming from there, that one's&nbsp;
coming from there, and two of these are coming&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:02.940
from there. Then when we add this one, we have&nbsp;
to put this 2 down here under the minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:08.160
and we have to put another one on top of the one,&nbsp;
so we get this picture here, which corresponds to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:13.920
the polynomial alpha to the minus two minus two&nbsp;
alpha to the minus one plus one plus three alpha.

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:21.720
Now the multiplication, however, is more&nbsp;
complicated and more interesting and corresponds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:21.720 --> 00:20:29.280
to what's called in measure theory convolution.&nbsp;
This convolution of these two measures,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:29.280 --> 00:20:35.520
let me try to illustrate what's going on here.&nbsp;
Here's the result that we get just by doing the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:42.480
algebraic product. The way we do it visually&nbsp;
is we say, okay, what we're going to do is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:47.040
we're going to take this thing here, think of this&nbsp;
thing as a fixed mass distribution which is sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:52.080
of centered at zero. It's centered at zero, fixed&nbsp;
mass distribution, and we're going to put various&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:52.080 --> 00:21:00.540
copies down of it in various positions to make&nbsp;
a cumulative mass distribution. The places where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.540 --> 00:21:08.460
those copies go and the sizes of the contributions&nbsp;
are determined by this one. Let me illustrate that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.460 --> 00:21:14.700
here. Over here, there is a one at minus two.&nbsp;
That's a minus two. What I'm going to do is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:14.700 --> 00:21:20.700
I'm going to move over here so that I'm sort of&nbsp;
centered at minus two temporarily, and I'm going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:25.860
to put a copy of this thing, which is currently&nbsp;
centered at zero. Just imagine copying it down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:32.160
here. So I'm not going to, maybe I'm not going to&nbsp;
write the bars, I'm just going to go like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.200 --> 00:21:39.780
representing that minus 2 there. That's sort&nbsp;
of one over from where we're centered here. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:39.780 --> 00:21:45.360
we've put that one there, and there's also a one&nbsp;
going up one to the right. So that one up there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:51.780
This mass distribution here is just a copy of&nbsp;
this one, but it's suitably translated so that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:51.780 --> 00:22:01.920
it's centered at minus two. Now the next one is&nbsp;
zero. So this thing here has a weight of zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:07.800
that means we have to take a copy of one of these&nbsp;
because it has weight to zero and translate it so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:13.260
that it's centered at zero. Well, that's exactly&nbsp;
where it is already. So that means we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:17.280
take this thing and basically just copy it&nbsp;
down here. So what does that mean? Well, under&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:23.160
minus one we have two. I'll do it&nbsp;
like that. Over one we have a one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:25.860 --> 00:22:31.740
We've copied this thing so it's centered at zero.&nbsp;
Now in addition, we have to take this thing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:31.740 --> 00:22:39.060
and we have to copy it so that it's centered at&nbsp;
one. But now we have to also double that mass&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:39.060 --> 00:22:44.280
distribution because there's a factor or weight&nbsp;
of two here. So really we have to take two times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:52.260
this thing and position it so that it's centered&nbsp;
at one. So let's do that. Let me take this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:57.060
here, and I'm going to center it at one, but I'm&nbsp;
also going to multiply it by two. So this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:57.060 --> 00:23:03.600
here, which is a weight of sort of negative two,&nbsp;
is going to come down from here to weight minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.600 --> 00:23:07.980
two, but then it's also going to keep going&nbsp;
exactly multiplied by two. So there's really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:15.840
a weight of 4 there. That's centered at one.&nbsp;
Then on the right of that at two, we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:21.240
also put one of these, but I also have to double&nbsp;
it, so not just one, I have to go up like this.

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:31.980
That's how we convolve things. We take a copy&nbsp;
of this thing and basically make copies of it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:31.980 --> 00:23:37.380
in various places determined by the positions&nbsp;
and the weights determined by this other one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:38.340 --> 00:23:42.360
Let me just see if we get the same thing that we&nbsp;
did algebraically. So here there's a minus two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:42.360 --> 00:23:47.040
alpha to the minus three, yes. What about alpha&nbsp;
to the minus one? Well, you see here there's some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:53.580
cancellation because there's sort of a positive&nbsp;
weight and there's also minus two weight, so the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:53.580 --> 00:23:58.920
total weight is minus one at minus one. So there's&nbsp;
a minus alpha minus one here, there's a weight of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:03.780
minus four, here there's a weight of plus one, and&nbsp;
here there's a weight of two at alpha squared. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:09.600
that's the same thing that we would get. Now you&nbsp;
can convince yourself that this is the same thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:09.600 --> 00:24:14.100
that we would get if we interchange the roles&nbsp;
of these two things. In other words, if we took&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:24.120
this thing and made copies of it according to the&nbsp;
weights and positions of these guys over here. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:31.920
I'll let you check that we're going to get the&nbsp;
same thing. This is showing you that in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:39.960
interpretation of having densities or measures,&nbsp;
the addition corresponds to just a cumulative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:48.540
addition of these measures in the simplest&nbsp;
possible way, while the multiplication is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:53.820
also attractive but corresponds to this&nbsp;
important operation called convolution,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:58.860
which is important in engineering and analysis&nbsp;
and many things. It arises in many places,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.860 --> 00:25:04.560
but this is an elementary way that it arises when&nbsp;
we have this interpretation of these integral poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:12.660
numbers as densities or measures on this&nbsp;
discrete number line labeled by integers.

00:25:13.320 --> 00:25:19.860
Now I want to suggest to you that this way of&nbsp;
thinking that I'm giving you here actually has a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:19.860 --> 00:25:26.820
really great consequence just a little bit further&nbsp;
down the road when we're in possession of rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:26.820 --> 00:25:32.760
numbers. So currently we've got natural numbers&nbsp;
and integers. We don't have rational numbers yet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.760 --> 00:25:37.920
but that will not be a big ask because we all&nbsp;
sort of know how to go from integers to rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:43.380
numbers in some fashion or another, in terms of&nbsp;
formal quotients or ordered pairs or something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:49.080
like that. So that's not going to be too much&nbsp;
work. But once we do have rational numbers as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:49.080 --> 00:25:54.600
part of our number system here, then we're going&nbsp;
to be able to adopt this point of view exactly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:54.600 --> 00:26:03.180
that I'm expressing here in this video to really&nbsp;
expand our minds about the objects that we think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:06.960
of in analysis in one way. We're going to be able&nbsp;
to think about them in a very different way from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:11.880
an algebraic point of view. So once we extend our&nbsp;
number system to the rational numbers, then we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:11.880 --> 00:26:16.440
make the following definition: that a rational&nbsp;
poly number is then an mset of rational numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:19.020 --> 00:26:26.880
Kind of obviously. For example, here then is&nbsp;
an mset of rational numbers. So here's rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:33.300
number two-thirds, two-thirds, 15 over seven,&nbsp;
zero. These bars over here are just negative,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:37.500
so this is negative two-thirds, negative&nbsp;
two-thirds, and this anti is the usual antis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:45.600
that's an anti-zero. In terms of a poly number or&nbsp;
a rational poly number, there's two of these minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:53.640
two-thirds, so that would correspond to, we would&nbsp;
write that down in alpha notation as 2 times alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:59.580
to the minus two-thirds because there's two-thirds&nbsp;
appearing here. Actually, minus two-thirds appear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:04.020
here, so we get alpha to the minus two-thirds,&nbsp;
two of them. There's a minus one because there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:04.020 --> 00:27:09.240
an anti-zero, and this fifteen over seven&nbsp;
would correspond to alpha to the 15 over 7.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.100 --> 00:27:17.760
Think about this for a second. We are creating&nbsp;
these things as legitimate mathematical objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:26.760
without a prior theory of cube roots or&nbsp;
seventh roots. If you go into a first-year&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:26.760 --> 00:27:32.820
calculus course and you say, what do we mean&nbsp;
by the function y equals x to the 15 over 7?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:37.800
Well, that's not going to be so easy for them&nbsp;
to explain. They'll try to tell you that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:37.800 --> 00:27:44.040
is a function that involves raising something&nbsp;
to the 15th power and also taking a one-seventh&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:47.460
root. Then you ask them, well, how do you take&nbsp;
a one-seventh root, and they go, I don't know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:47.460 --> 00:27:53.340
you use a calculator. So that's the way they think&nbsp;
about it. They think this is something that inputs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:53.340 --> 00:27:58.020
a number and then you have to use a calculator&nbsp;
involving this rather complicated seventh root&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:58.020 --> 00:28:05.460
operation in order to calculate the result.&nbsp;
What we're doing here is invoking this as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:05.460 --> 00:28:10.680
legitimate mathematical object without any mention&nbsp;
of seventh roots or cube roots or anything else.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:19.740
It's just a multi-set of rational numbers,&nbsp;
and it can be represented physically in a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:19.740 --> 00:28:25.440
parallel way to what I've already explained.&nbsp;
It's just that now our number line is to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:25.440 --> 00:28:30.840
thought of as being expanded, not just discrete&nbsp;
in terms of the natural numbers or the integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:30.840 --> 00:28:37.800
we're also considering rational number positions,&nbsp;
rational numbers completely obtainable in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:44.160
finite amount of way, no infinite processes or&nbsp;
dreaming required. So this thing here, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:48.660
we just find the point minus two-thirds on our&nbsp;
number line somewhere between zero and minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:54.960
and over that point, well, there's two of these,&nbsp;
so we put a weight of two over minus two-thirds.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:58.140 --> 00:29:03.060
Anti, oh, here's zero, yes, here's zero, there's&nbsp;
minus one of them, so we put a weight of minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:07.380
one at zero, and over here, fifteen over&nbsp;
seven, it's a little bit more than two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:07.380 --> 00:29:13.380
there's that point. Over that point,&nbsp;
we put a weight of one. So there it is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:15.240 --> 00:29:22.020
there's no irrationalities involved here at all,&nbsp;
there's no irrationalities in sight whatsoever.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:30.600
That is such an important point to make. We&nbsp;
are doing something different from what you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:30.600 --> 00:29:35.160
find in undergraduate courses. We're looking&nbsp;
at things from a different point of view.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:43.200
It's all just msets. Now with this framework,&nbsp;
we're in a position to introduce something really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:43.200 --> 00:29:51.360
exciting, which is a fundamental symmetry in this&nbsp;
situation. Here's our number line: there's zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:56.160
natural numbers over here, one, two, three,&nbsp;
negative numbers over here, minus one, minus two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:56.160 --> 00:30:00.960
minus three. There is a symmetry here. We&nbsp;
can look this way, we can look this way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:05.460
they look pretty well the same in both directions,&nbsp;
just this is going to the right and this is going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:05.460 --> 00:30:12.120
to the left for you. It is the symmetry, that&nbsp;
reflection symmetry about this central point.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:18.240
If you've been watching my math and music&nbsp;
series, I talk about symmetry in the piano&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:24.060
and the difference between translation&nbsp;
symmetry and reflection symmetry. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:24.060 --> 00:30:29.460
actually an important topic. This is an&nbsp;
example of where the reflection symmetry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:29.460 --> 00:30:37.860
about zero plays an important role. Typically&nbsp;
speaking, if we're thinking of a number line as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:43.620
giving us positional information, we have&nbsp;
some physical structure and we want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:51.480
allocate positions to various things, maybe&nbsp;
it's a road and these are our street numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:57.120
or it's an industrial assembly line and here's&nbsp;
the various markers on the assembly line.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:57.660 --> 00:31:03.360
When we have that kind of thing, the translation&nbsp;
invariance is almost always more important than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:03.360 --> 00:31:09.840
the symmetry. But in this situation here, we're&nbsp;
looking at the number line as a representation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:09.840 --> 00:31:15.480
of this arithmetical structure. It's not just&nbsp;
positions we're talking about, we're talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:15.480 --> 00:31:23.940
having arithmetic here, and in arithmetic, zero&nbsp;
does play a very distinguished role. Zero is very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:23.940 --> 00:31:30.960
special, it's like the most important point on the&nbsp;
number line. So the symmetry about zero naturally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:36.300
plays a role in arithmetic, as opposed to the&nbsp;
piano, you're not doing arithmetic on the keys,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:40.200
you're just going up and down. It's the&nbsp;
translation invariance that's important.

00:31:40.200 --> 00:31:45.120
So what we're going to do now is to look&nbsp;
carefully at this fundamental symmetry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:45.120 --> 00:31:51.240
that's appearing here, which is largely&nbsp;
invisible to undergraduates. Because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:52.140 --> 00:31:55.440
from an undergraduate point of view, as&nbsp;
we've talked about already, there's a big&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:55.440 --> 00:32:00.660
difference between the function f of x equals&nbsp;
x and the function f of x equals 1 over x.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:01.200 --> 00:32:05.160
There's not a lot of similarity between&nbsp;
those two things. They're very different,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:05.160 --> 00:32:10.020
they look different, their graphs are different,&nbsp;
their integration theories are different, their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:10.020 --> 00:32:18.000
arc length formulas are completely different, etc.&nbsp;
But we're moving away from the calculus point and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:22.740
just looking at this algebraic side of things,&nbsp;
and there the symmetry is really important. So an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:22.740 --> 00:32:30.780
example: here is an integral poly number weighted&nbsp;
one minus one, weight of minus one at one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:30.780 --> 00:32:38.220
a weight of three at two. So it's alpha minus&nbsp;
1, minus alpha plus 3 alpha squared. Here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:38.820 --> 00:32:44.580
this reflection symmetry, let's call it sigma.&nbsp;
Sigma, and what does this do? Well, it just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:45.360 --> 00:32:50.460
reflects everything around zero.&nbsp;
So that tower goes over there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:51.360 --> 00:32:55.620
and this little underneath thing goes over on this&nbsp;
side, and this thing here goes on the other side.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:56.820 --> 00:33:02.340
Algebraically, what we do is we&nbsp;
just negate all the exponents,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:02.340 --> 00:33:08.580
so we're getting three alpha to the minus&nbsp;
two, minus alpha to the minus one, plus alpha.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:09.300 --> 00:33:15.120
More generally, sigma of alpha to the n&nbsp;
equals alpha to the minus n, and otherwise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:21.720
we're sort of using linearity to extend that&nbsp;
to more general poly numbers or I poly numbers.

00:33:23.940 --> 00:33:31.140
Now this symmetry operation on integral poly&nbsp;
numbers satisfies a number of pleasant properties.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:31.980 --> 00:33:36.720
The first one is that it's an involution, that&nbsp;
if you do it twice, you get back to where you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:41.220
started. You reflect and reflect again, you're&nbsp;
back to where you are. So sigma of sigma of p&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:41.220 --> 00:33:47.520
equals p. It's linear, sigma of p plus q equals&nbsp;
sigma of p plus sigma of q. It's also linear in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:54.000
the sense that if k is an integer, you multiply&nbsp;
a poly number by two and then reflect, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:58.140
you're going to get twice the reflection of&nbsp;
the original. This one here is a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:58.140 --> 00:34:04.860
more subtle: that's the sigma of a product is&nbsp;
the product of the sigmas. Sigma of pq equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:04.860 --> 00:34:13.140
sigma of p times sigma of q. So this is a&nbsp;
pretty natural algebraic symmetry which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:13.140 --> 00:34:20.220
in some sense at the heart of algebra when we&nbsp;
look at integral poly numbers in this fashion.

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:26.580
For our last slide, we're going to introduce&nbsp;
symmetric and alternating integral poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:32.160
We'll say that a poly number, an integral poly&nbsp;
number, is symmetric precisely when sigma of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:32.160 --> 00:34:38.580
p equals p. That means that when you look at it,&nbsp;
it's symmetric. Everything to the right looks very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:38.580 --> 00:34:43.680
much like everything to the left symmetrically. So&nbsp;
for example, this thing here, 2 times alpha to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:43.680 --> 00:34:50.400
minus 3 minus 4 alpha to the minus 1 plus 1&nbsp;
minus 4 alpha plus 2 alpha cubed is symmetric.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:51.660 --> 00:34:57.960
Conversely, p is alternating, or maybe in some&nbsp;
other context, we could say skew-symmetric or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:57.960 --> 00:35:06.480
anti-symmetric. Let's use alternating when sigma&nbsp;
of p equals minus p, same as p bar. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:12.660
this one here, q equals three alpha to the&nbsp;
minus five minus alpha to the minus 1 plus alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:13.380 --> 00:35:19.260
minus 3 alpha to the five, this thing's&nbsp;
alternating because when you apply sigma,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:24.960
you're going to get minus 3 alpha&nbsp;
to the minus 5 plus alpha inverse&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:24.960 --> 00:35:29.580
minus alpha plus 3 alpha. You're going to&nbsp;
get exactly the negative of this thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:38.700
So having this sigma reflection allows us&nbsp;
to identify two sort of interesting classes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:38.700 --> 00:35:45.000
two particularly natural classes, of&nbsp;
integral poly numbers: the symmetric ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:45.600 --> 00:35:52.740
and the alternating ones. In fact, there is&nbsp;
a nice way of cooking these up in quite great&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:52.740 --> 00:35:59.100
generality. So if you have any integral poly&nbsp;
number p, then p plus sigma of p is symmetric,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:00.540 --> 00:36:06.000
whereas p minus sigma of p is&nbsp;
alternating. That's an easy check.

00:36:08.460 --> 00:36:17.760
So now we're at the door of a kind of untold&nbsp;
chapter of algebra, a missing chapter of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:22.560
algebra that probably you should have learned&nbsp;
about in grade nine or grade ten when you were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:22.560 --> 00:36:28.440
learning about polynomials. But at that time, you&nbsp;
thought that polynomials were only things that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:35.040
you cooked up with positive powers of x or y or&nbsp;
whatever, but not from this larger point of view:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:35.040 --> 00:36:43.740
positive powers, negative powers. These things&nbsp;
are naturally viewed together. When we do that, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:43.740 --> 00:36:51.840
come to this new chapter of algebra, which we're&nbsp;
going to start investigating next time, and there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:57.900
will be all kinds of interesting consequences with&nbsp;
some actually quite sophisticated mathematics and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:57.900 --> 00:37:03.240
physics. Hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:03.668
[Music]

